Q: Safari UI appears in iOS PWA after navigating from Dashboard to another route A: <p>Most likely Safari is installing your app with a non root scope when you add it from <code>/dashboard</code>. Then, when you navigate to <code>/messenger</code>, iOS treats it as outside the app context and shows Safari controls.</p>
<p><strong>First try make the manifest URL absolute and identical on every route</strong></p>
<p>If your <code>&lt;link rel=&quot;manifest&quot;&gt;</code> is relative,</p>
<pre class="lang-html prettyprint-override"><code>&lt;link rel=&quot;manifest&quot; href=&quot;manifest.webmanifest&quot;&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>then on <code>/dashboard</code> it resolves to <code>/dashboard/manifest.webmanifest</code>, which can lead to a different scope.</p>
<p>So use an absolute path and put it in the root layout / document so it’s not route dependent:</p>
<p>(Your Next.js App Router (<code>app/layout.tsx</code>))</p>
<pre class="lang-tsx prettyprint-override"><code>export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    &lt;html lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;
      &lt;head&gt;
        &lt;link rel=&quot;manifest&quot; href=&quot;/manifest.webmanifest&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/head&gt;
      &lt;body&gt;{children}&lt;/body&gt;
    &lt;/html&gt;
  );
}
</code></pre>
<p>(Your Next.js Pages Router (<code>pages/_document.tsx</code>))</p>
<pre class="lang-tsx prettyprint-override"><code>import { Html, Head, Main, NextScript } from &quot;next/document&quot;;

export default function Document() {
  return (
    &lt;Html&gt;
      &lt;Head&gt;
        &lt;link rel=&quot;manifest&quot; href=&quot;/manifest.webmanifest&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/Head&gt;
      &lt;body&gt;
        &lt;Main /&gt;
        &lt;NextScript /&gt;
      &lt;/body&gt;
    &lt;/Html&gt;
  );
}
</code></pre>
<p>And check it:</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>document.querySelector('link[rel=&quot;manifest&quot;]')?.href
</code></pre>
<p>It must always be <code>https://your-domain.com/manifest.webmanifest</code> regardless of the current route.</p>
<p><strong>And also try another fix explicitly, set <code>scope</code> and <code>start_url</code> to the root</strong></p>
<p>In <code>manifest.webmanifest</code> ensure you pin the app boundaries:</p>
<pre class="lang-json prettyprint-override"><code>{
  &quot;name&quot;: &quot;My App&quot;,
  &quot;short_name&quot;: &quot;MyApp&quot;,
  &quot;display&quot;: &quot;standalone&quot;,
  &quot;start_url&quot;: &quot;/?source=pwa&quot;,
  &quot;scope&quot;: &quot;/&quot;,
  &quot;id&quot;: &quot;/&quot;,
  &quot;icons&quot;: [
    { &quot;src&quot;: &quot;/icons/icon-192.png&quot;, &quot;sizes&quot;: &quot;192x192&quot;, &quot;type&quot;: &quot;image/png&quot; },
    { &quot;src&quot;: &quot;/icons/icon-512.png&quot;, &quot;sizes&quot;: &quot;512x512&quot;, &quot;type&quot;: &quot;image/png&quot; }
  ]
}
</code></pre>
<ul>
<li><code>scope: &quot;/&quot;</code> makes all routes (<code>/dashboard</code>, <code>/messenger</code>, etc.) part of the app.</li>
<li><code>start_url: &quot;/&quot;</code> prevents the install route from becoming the app entry.</li>
<li><code>id: &quot;/&quot;</code> helps keep it treated as the same app install.</li>
</ul>
<p>After changing these, delete the existing Home Screen icon and reinstall, because iOS Safari aggressively caches the installed web app metadata.</p>

Q: I have a table. When I click on the ref. num. of a row, a form will popup. How do I display that row data in another file when I click submit in form? A: <p>Since you said you are not very familiar with JavaScript, let me give an answer.</p>
<p>(A) Let's simplify the code to display &quot;ReferenceNumber&quot; and &quot;name&quot; only</p>
<p>(B) I will use jquery modal (v.0.9x, jquery-modal stable version) to do the job to pop-up the modal (but you are free to use other ways, of course)</p>
<p><strong>Jobs to perform:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Build the table from data (I am using arrays to demonstrate
)</li>
<li>When you click the &quot;[click me]&quot; hyperlink, it calls the openLoginPopup JS function, passing the <code>ReferenceNumber</code> and <code>name</code> as parameters</li>
<li>The JS will populate the appropriate elements in the modal box, and then trigger the modal pop-up</li>
</ol>
<p>So the code is :</p>
<p>test.php</p>
<pre><code>&lt;script
  src=&quot;https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.7.1.js&quot;
  integrity=&quot;sha256-eKhayi8LEQwp4NKxN+CfCh+3qOVUtJn3QNZ0TciWLP4=&quot;
  crossorigin=&quot;anonymous&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;!-- jQuery Modal --&gt;
&lt;script src=&quot;https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/jquery-modal/0.9.1/jquery.modal.min.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; href=&quot;https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/jquery-modal/0.9.1/jquery.modal.min.css&quot; /&gt;

&lt;!-- Modal HTML embedded directly into document --&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;ex1&quot; class=&quot;modal&quot;&gt;
&lt;div id=modalref&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;div id=modalname&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;form action=view.php method=POST&gt;
  &lt;input type=hidden id=modalref2 name=refnum&gt;
  &lt;input type=submit value=&quot;Pass to view.php&quot;&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;script&gt;

function openLoginPopup(var1, var2) {
   document.getElementById('modalref').innerHTML=var1;
   document.getElementById('modalname').innerHTML=var2;
   document.getElementById('modalref2').value=var1;
   $('#ex1').modal('show');

}
&lt;/script&gt;   

&lt;?php
$collectLeaveDetails = [
    [
        &quot;ReferenceNumber&quot;=&gt;1,
        &quot;name&quot; =&gt; &quot;Aloe Vera&quot;
    ],
    [
        &quot;ReferenceNumber&quot;=&gt;2,
        &quot;name&quot; =&gt; &quot;Catnip&quot;
    ],
    [
        &quot;ReferenceNumber&quot;=&gt;3,
        &quot;name&quot; =&gt; &quot;Rosemary&quot;
    ]
];
?&gt;

&lt;table border = 1 cellspacing = 0 cellpadding = 10&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;No.&lt;td&gt;Name&lt;td&gt;Action

&lt;?php
 $i = 1;
 foreach ($collectLeaveDetails as $cld) {
?&gt;
&lt;tr class = &quot;rowcolor&quot;&gt;
     &lt;td style = &quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;?=$i;?&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
     &lt;td style = &quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;?=$cld['name'];?&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
     &lt;td style = &quot;cursor: pointer&quot; onclick = &quot;openLoginPopup(&lt;?=$cld['ReferenceNumber'];?&gt;, '&lt;?=$cld['name'];?&gt;');&quot;&gt;
        [Click Me]
     &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;?php
     ++$i;
 }
 ?&gt;
&lt;/table&gt; 
</code></pre>
<p>and the following is the view.php</p>
<pre><code>&lt;?php
$rn = $_POST['refnum'];
echo $rn;
?&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>The result will be:</p>
<p><a href="https://i.sstatic.net/JdDpQm2C.jpg" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><img src="https://i.sstatic.net/JdDpQm2C.jpg" alt="enter image description here" /></a></p>
<p>and when click the hyperlink, the following will be displayed:</p>
<p><a href="https://i.sstatic.net/D8vIif4E.jpg" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><img src="https://i.sstatic.net/D8vIif4E.jpg" alt="enter image description here" /></a></p>
<p>Now you may click the button &quot;Pass to view.php&quot; and the &quot;Reference Number&quot; will be displayed (in the above screen, it will be &quot;2&quot; displayed by view.php)</p>
<p>I believe the above has demonstrated the core concepts, please amend the code to suit your needs.</p>
